[2] Australia (NSW)
Date: Fri 11 Mar 2011
Source: The Blacktown Sun [edited]
<http://www.blacktownsun.com.au/news/local/news/general/warning-on-measles-outbreak-in-blacktown-local-government-area/2100834.aspx>

Warning on measles outbreak in Blacktown local government area
--------------------------------------------------------------
Residents have been warned of a measles outbreak
in the Blacktown local government area. Dr Vicky
Sheppeard, manager, NSW Health Communicable
Diseases for the public health unit said there
had been 14 confirmed cases since the end of
January [2011] at Rooty Hill, Seven Hills, Mt Druitt and St Marys.

She said the initial symptoms of measles was
fever, tiredness, runny nose,cough and sore red
eyes. "Symptoms usually begin around 10 days
after contact with an infected person, so people
need to be aware of any signs of infection in
themselves or their children during this week,"
she said. "A red, blotchy rash would appear 3 to
3 days after initial symptoms. The rash starts on
the face and then spreads over the body and will
last 3 to 3 days. Anyone who develops these
symptoms should seek advice from their GP.

"We ask that people to ring ahead to say that
they could have measles and ask to be seated in a
separate waiting room to avoid spreading the
disease to others. Measles is one of the most
easily spread diseases and just being in the same
room as someone with measles can result in
infection. Around one in 5 people who catch
measles require hospitalisation, so it's better
to prevent catching it if possible. The public
health unit has been working with local
hospitals, GPs and schools to identify and
contact people who may have been exposed to the infection."

Dr Sheppeard said it was important for people who
had not been immunised to watch out for these
symptoms as they may have come in contact with
the disease. Children should be vaccinated
against measles at one year and 4 years of age.
For adults between 25 and 45 years old, who are
often as susceptible to measles as when they were
young, only one dose of vaccine was recommended.

[Byline: Nick Soon]

--
