[4] Spain (Seville)
Date: Mon 14 Mar 2011
Source: El Mundo, Europa Press, Sevilla [machine
translation, paraphrased & edited]
<http://www.diariodesevilla.es/article/sevilla/927645/brote/sarampion/afecta/casos/pero/sas/asegura/esta/controlado.html>


240 people affected by an outbreak of measles
---------------------------------------------
The Health Ministry on Monday [14 Mar 2011]
stated that the number of people affected by the
outbreak of measles which began in January [2011]
in Seville and its surrounding province had risen
to 240, but was now believed to be contained.

Health Department sources stated that the number
of people affected by measles in the municipality
of San Juan de Aznalfarache had now reached 109,
an outbreak that is linked to that recorded in
Seville, particularly in the neighborhoods of La
Plata, and Litanies Poligono Sur. The number of
cases in this linked outbreak has rises to 47, of
which 12 are located in La Plata, 19 in Las
Litaneias and 16 in Litanies Poligono Sur.

Besides these cases, the Health Ministry has
recorded 84 others measles case in Seville and
its province, but these cases are considered
"sporadic;" i.e, unrelated epidemiologically to
the above outbreak, and considered to be "under control."

In Seville on Monday the Minister of Health,
Maria Jesus Montero, responding to questions from
reporters stated that there had been a massive
positive response to the call for vaccination in
contrast to the situation in Granada "where some
families had been reluctant to be vaccinated."

The Health Department emphasized the need to
achieve protection of all children by vaccination
in view of the contagiousness of measles. For
this reason and in view of the exceptional
circumstances it was essential to vaccinate all
6-month-old children in the slums of South Range,
Litany and La Plata. Children under 6 months of
age are naturally immunized (from the mother
during pregnancy and through subsequent breast-feeding).

--
